Q1.  What is the difference between compiler and interpreter?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys
A:   A compiler translates the ENTIRE source code to machine code before
     execution (e.g., C++). An interpreter translates and executes LINE BY
     LINE at runtime (e.g., Python).
     Key differences:
     - Compiler: faster execution, errors shown after full scan
     - Interpreter: slower, errors shown line by line, easier to debug
     - C++ is compiled; Java compiles to bytecode, then JVM interprets it

Q2.  What happens during compilation of a C++ program step by step?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Google
A:   4 stages:
     1. Preprocessing  — processes #include, #define, macros → expanded .cpp
     2. Compilation    — converts .cpp to assembly (.s file)
     3. Assembly       — converts assembly to object code (.o / .obj)
     4. Linking        — combines .o files + libraries → final executable
     Run manually: g++ -E (preprocess), -S (compile), -c (assemble), then link

Q3.  What is the difference between #include <file> and #include "file"?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, L&T Infotech
A:   <file>   → searches system/standard library include directories only
     "file"   → searches current directory FIRST, then system directories
     Rule: use <> for standard headers (#include <iostream>),
           use "" for your own project headers (#include "myheader.h")

Q4.  What is a header guard? Why is it needed?
     Asked at: L&T Infotech, Persistent
A:   A header guard prevents a header file from being included more than once
     in the same translation unit, which would cause redefinition errors.
     Syntax:
         #ifndef MY_HEADER_H
         #define MY_HEADER_H
         // header content
         #endif
     Modern alternative: #pragma once (non-standard but universally supported)
     Without it: if two files both include the same header, redefinition occurs.

Q5.  What is the difference between declaration and definition?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys
A:   Declaration: tells the compiler a name and its type EXIST — no memory
     allocated yet. Example: extern int x;  or  void foo(int);
     Definition: allocates memory / provides the actual body.
     Example: int x = 5;  or  void foo(int a) { return a; }
     Rule: you can declare many times, but define ONLY ONCE (One Definition Rule)

Q6.  What does return 0 mean in main()?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys
A:   return 0 signals SUCCESSFUL termination to the operating system.
     Non-zero values indicate error codes (e.g., return 1 → general error).
     In C++, if you omit the return statement in main(), the compiler implicitly
     inserts return 0. This is unique to main() — other functions don't get this.

Q7.  What is undefined behavior in C++? Give an example.
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Google
A:   Undefined behavior (UB) is code whose outcome is NOT specified by the C++
     standard. The program may crash, give wrong output, or appear to work —
     and this can vary by compiler, optimization level, and platform.
     Common examples:
     - Signed integer overflow:      int x = INT_MAX; x++;
     - Out-of-bounds array access:   int a[5]; a[10] = 1;
     - Null/dangling pointer deref:  int* p = nullptr; *p = 5;
     - Using uninitialized variable: int x; cout << x;
     - Modifying a string literal:   char* s = "hi"; s[0] = 'H';
     UB is dangerous because it can silently corrupt data or work in debug
     builds but crash in release builds.

Q8.  What is the difference between i++ and ++i? Which is preferred and why?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Zoho, Amazon
A:   i++ (post-increment): returns the ORIGINAL value, THEN increments.
     ++i (pre-increment):  increments FIRST, THEN returns the new value.
     Example:
         int i = 5;
         cout << i++;  // prints 5, then i becomes 6
         cout << ++i;  // i becomes 7, prints 7
     In simple loops (for(int i=0; i<n; i++)), both produce identical results
     because the returned value is discarded.
     PREFERENCE: ++i is preferred for iterators and objects because i++ creates
     a temporary copy of the old value, which is unnecessary overhead.
     For primitives, modern compilers optimize them identically.

Q9.  What is short-circuit evaluation in logical operators?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft
A:   Short-circuit means the second operand is NOT evaluated if the result is
     already determined from the first.
     && (AND): if left is FALSE → skip right (result is already false)
     || (OR):  if left is TRUE  → skip right (result is already true)
     Practical use — safe null check:
         if (ptr != nullptr && ptr->value > 0)  // ptr->value never runs if ptr is null
     Trap — side effects may not execute:
         if (++x > 0 || ++y > 0)  // y may NOT be incremented!

Q10. What is the difference between = and ==?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys
A:   = is the ASSIGNMENT operator — stores a value into a variable.
     == is the EQUALITY COMPARISON — checks if two values are equal, returns bool.
     Classic bug: if (x = 5) — this ASSIGNS 5 to x (always true since 5 != 0)
     Correct:     if (x == 5) — this COMPARES x with 5
     Tip: write constants on the left (Yoda condition) to catch this:
         if (5 == x) — compiler errors if you accidentally write if (5 = x)

Q11. Explain operator precedence with an example.
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Zoho
A:   Operator precedence determines which operator is evaluated first in an
     expression with multiple operators.
     Example: 2 + 3 * 4 = 14  (not 20) because * > + in precedence.
     Key order (high → low):
     () > ! ~ ++ -- > * / % > + - > << >> > < <= >= > == != >
     & > ^ > | > && > || > ?: > =
     Always use parentheses to make intent explicit and avoid bugs:
         int x = (a > b) ? a : b;   // clear and safe

Q12. What is the difference between / and % operators?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys
A:   / is division:
         int: 7 / 2 = 3   (truncates toward zero, integer division)
         float: 7.0 / 2.0 = 3.5
     % is modulo (remainder):
         7 % 2 = 1,   10 % 3 = 1,   -7 % 2 = -1 (sign follows dividend in C++)
     % only works with INTEGER types — using it on float is a compile error.
     Common use: even/odd check (n % 2 == 0), cycling through indices (i % n)

Q13. What is integer overflow? How do you prevent it?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Google
A:   Integer overflow occurs when arithmetic result exceeds the type's range.
     int range: roughly -2.1 billion to +2.1 billion.
     INT_MAX + 1 wraps to INT_MIN (undefined behavior for signed integers).
     Prevention strategies:
     - Use long long for large values in DSA/competitive programming
     - Check before operation: if (a > INT_MAX - b) { /* overflow */ }
     - Use __int128 for very large intermediate values
     - Use std::numeric_limits<int>::max() to get the max value portably
     Note: unsigned overflow is DEFINED (wraps modulo 2^N), signed is UB.

Q14. What is the difference between int, long, long long?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Amazon
A:   int      → 4 bytes, range: ~-2.1B to +2.1B (guaranteed ≥ 16 bits)
     long     → at least 4 bytes (4 on Windows 64-bit, 8 on Linux 64-bit)
     long long → exactly 8 bytes, range: ~-9.2 quintillion to +9.2 quintillion
     For competitive programming and DSA: ALWAYS use long long when values
     can exceed 10^9. Many problems give TLE or WA due to int overflow.
     Quick check: if N > ~2*10^9, use long long.

Q15. When would you use unsigned int over int?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, Samsung, Sasken
A:   Use unsigned int when:
     - Values are inherently non-negative (array sizes, counts, bit masks)
     - You need to double the positive range (0 to ~4.2 billion)
     - Working with bit manipulation (logical right shift behavior is defined)
     - Interfacing with hardware registers or network protocols
     WARNING: Mixing signed and unsigned in comparisons is dangerous.
     Example: int x = -1; unsigned int y = 1; if (x < y) — this is FALSE
     because -1 is implicitly converted to a very large unsigned number!

Q16. What is the size of int on a 32-bit vs 64-bit system?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Samsung, Sasken
A:   int is 4 bytes (32 bits) on BOTH 32-bit and 64-bit systems in C++.
     The C++ standard guarantees int is AT LEAST 16 bits, but in practice
     all modern compilers use 4 bytes for int regardless of platform.
     What changes on 64-bit: long (4 bytes on Windows, 8 bytes on Linux/Mac),
     pointer size (4 bytes on 32-bit, 8 bytes on 64-bit).
     Use sizeof(int) to check at runtime.

Q17. What is the auto keyword in C++? When should you use it?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Google
A:   auto tells the compiler to DEDUCE the type from the initializer expression.
         auto x = 10;              // x is int
         auto d = 3.14;            // d is double
         auto it = vec.begin();    // saves writing std::vector<int>::iterator
         auto f = [](int x){ return x*2; };  // lambda type
     WHEN TO USE:
     - Iterator types (long and verbose)
     - Lambda variables (type is unnamed)
     - When the type is obvious from the right-hand side
     WHEN TO AVOID:
     - When type is not obvious: auto x = foo(); — reader can't tell what x is
     - When you need a specific type: auto x = 5; gives int, not long long

Q18. What is the difference between const int x and int const x?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Persistent
A:   For SIMPLE variables: they are IDENTICAL — both make x a constant integer.
         const int x = 5;   // x cannot be changed
         int const x = 5;   // same thing
     The difference matters with POINTERS:
         const int* p  — pointer to const int  (value can't change, address can)
         int* const p  — const pointer to int  (address can't change, value can)
         const int* const p — both are const
     Rule: read right-to-left from the variable name:
     "p is a const pointer to int" vs "p is a pointer to const int"

Q19. What is constexpr? How is it different from const?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Google, Atlassian
A:   const: the value cannot change after initialization, but it CAN be set
     at runtime.
         const int n = getInput();  // OK: runtime constant
     constexpr: value MUST be known and evaluated at COMPILE TIME.
         constexpr int SIZE = 10;   // OK: compile-time constant
         constexpr int bad = getInput(); // ERROR: not compile-time
     constexpr enables use in:
     - Array sizes: int arr[SIZE];
     - Template parameters: template<int N>
     - switch case labels
     constexpr functions are evaluated at compile time if inputs are constexpr.
     In modern C++, prefer constexpr over const for true compile-time constants.

Q20. What is a magic number? Why should you avoid it?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro
A:   A magic number is a raw numeric literal in code with no explanation of
     what it represents.
     Bad:   if (status == 3) { ... }   // what does 3 mean?
            int arr[86400];             // why 86400?
     Good:  const int LOGGED_IN = 3;
            constexpr int SECONDS_PER_DAY = 86400;
     Why avoid:
     - Reader has no idea what the number means
     - If the value changes, you must find and update every occurrence
     - Leads to bugs when one instance is updated but another is missed
     Solution: always name constants with descriptive names.

