Q21. What are the storage classes in C/C++? Explain each.
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys, L&T Infotech, Mphasis
A:   auto     — default for local variables; allocated on stack; destroyed
                when scope ends. (In C++11+, auto has a new meaning for type
                deduction — the storage class meaning is deprecated.)
     register — hint to compiler to store variable in CPU register for speed.
                Mostly ignored by modern compilers.
     static   — local: retains value between function calls, lives in data
                segment. Global: limits visibility to the translation unit.
     extern   — declares a variable that is defined in ANOTHER translation
                unit. Used to share globals across files.
     mutable  — allows a data member of a const object to be modified.
                Used in caching/lazy evaluation inside const methods.

Q22. What does static mean for a local variable?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, L&T Infotech, Persistent
A:   A static local variable:
     - Is initialized ONLY ONCE (first time the function is called)
     - RETAINS its value between function calls
     - Lives in the DATA SEGMENT (not the stack)
     - Is destroyed only when the program ends
     Example:
         void counter() {
             static int count = 0;   // initialized once
             count++;
             cout << count;
         }
         counter(); // prints 1
         counter(); // prints 2
         counter(); // prints 3
     Use cases: counting calls, singleton pattern, caching expensive results.

Q23. What does static mean for a global variable?
     Asked at: L&T Infotech, Sasken
A:   A static global variable has INTERNAL LINKAGE — it is only visible within
     the translation unit (source file) where it is defined. Other .cpp files
     cannot access it via extern.
     Without static: the global is visible to all translation units (external
     linkage), which can cause name collisions across files.
     Example:
         // file1.cpp
         static int counter = 0;  // only file1.cpp can see this
     Modern C++ prefers anonymous namespaces for this purpose:
         namespace { int counter = 0; }  // same effect, more idiomatic

Q24. What is variable shadowing? Give an example.
     Asked at: Zoho, Persistent
A:   Variable shadowing occurs when a variable in an inner scope has the same
     name as a variable in an outer scope. The inner one "hides" the outer one
     within that scope.
         int x = 10;
         {
             int x = 20;  // shadows outer x
             cout << x;   // prints 20
         }
         cout << x;       // prints 10 (outer x restored)
     Risks: accidental modification of the wrong variable, confusion.
     Many compilers warn about this with -Wshadow flag.
     Best practice: use distinct names, especially for member variables
     vs local variables.

Q25. What is a namespace? How does it help avoid name collisions?
     Asked at: L&T Infotech, Persistent, Nagarro
A:   A namespace groups related identifiers under a named scope to prevent
     naming conflicts across large codebases or multiple libraries.
         namespace MathLib {
             int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
         }
         namespace StringLib {
             int add(string a, string b) { ... }
         }
         MathLib::add(3, 4);    // unambiguous
         StringLib::add("x","y");
     std:: is the standard library namespace.
     using namespace std; — brings all std names into scope (convenient but
     risky in large codebases — can cause collisions).

Q26. What is an anonymous namespace? How is it different from static?
     Asked at: Advanced C++ roles, Sasken
A:   An anonymous namespace restricts identifiers to the current translation
     unit, giving them internal linkage — exactly like static for globals.
         namespace {
             int helper = 0;   // only visible in this file
             void helperFn() { }
         }
     Differences from static:
     - Applies to ALL declarations in the block (functions, classes, types)
     - static only works on variables and functions, NOT type declarations
     - Anonymous namespace is the PREFERRED modern C++ approach
     Both prevent external linkage; anonymous namespace is more versatile.

Q27. What are the 4 types of casts in C++?
     Asked at: L&T Infotech, Persistent, Nagarro, Zoho
A:   1. static_cast — safe compile-time cast between compatible types
           double d = static_cast<double>(5);  // int → double
           No runtime check. Most common and safest.
     2. dynamic_cast — runtime polymorphic cast (needs virtual functions)
           Derived* d = dynamic_cast<Derived*>(basePtr);
           Returns nullptr if cast fails (for pointers). Costs RTTI lookup.
     3. const_cast — adds or removes const/volatile qualifiers
           const_cast<int*>(constPtr)  // remove const (use carefully!)
     4. reinterpret_cast — low-level bit reinterpretation, unsafe
           int* p = reinterpret_cast<int*>(somePtr);  // unsafe!
     Prefer static_cast over C-style (Type)x casts for clarity and safety.

Q28. When would you use static_cast vs reinterpret_cast?
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro, Samsung
A:   static_cast: use for logically meaningful, type-safe conversions
     - int ↔ double, int ↔ float, base* ↔ derived* (no runtime check),
       explicit constructor conversions
     - Compiler checks that the conversion makes sense
     reinterpret_cast: use for low-level bit reinterpretation with NO
     type checking
     - Converting between pointer types (void* ↔ int*)
     - Hardware register access in embedded systems
     - Serialization tricks
     Rule: if static_cast compiles, prefer it. Use reinterpret_cast only when
     you KNOW what you're doing at the bit level.

Q29. What is dynamic_cast? What is RTTI? What is its cost?
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro, Advanced C++ roles
A:   dynamic_cast performs SAFE RUNTIME downcasting in polymorphic class
     hierarchies. It checks at runtime whether the cast is valid.
         Base* b = new Derived();
         Derived* d = dynamic_cast<Derived*>(b);  // succeeds, returns valid ptr
         Other* o = dynamic_cast<Other*>(b);       // fails, returns nullptr
     RTTI (Run-Time Type Information): metadata the compiler attaches to
     every polymorphic object (class with at least one virtual function).
     dynamic_cast uses RTTI to verify the actual runtime type.
     Cost: small runtime overhead (vtable lookup + type comparison).
     Can be disabled with -fno-rtti for performance-critical code.

Q30. What is const_cast? When is it safe to use?
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro
A:   const_cast removes or adds const/volatile qualifiers from a variable.
         void print(char* str);  // legacy function, doesn't modify str
         const char* msg = "hello";
         print(const_cast<char*>(msg));  // safe: we know print won't modify it
     SAFE to use: when the original object was NOT declared const and you
     need to pass it to a legacy API that takes a non-const pointer.
     UNSAFE / UNDEFINED BEHAVIOR: if you use const_cast to actually MODIFY
     an object that was originally declared const:
         const int x = 5;
         *const_cast<int*>(&x) = 10;  // UB: modifying a truly const object
     Use with extreme care — it's mostly a workaround for legacy code.

Q31. What is implicit type conversion? What is explicit?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, L&T Infotech
A:   Implicit conversion: compiler automatically converts one type to another
     without programmer instruction.
         int x = 5;
         double d = x;  // int implicitly promoted to double
         bool b = x;    // non-zero → true
     Explicit conversion: programmer manually specifies the conversion.
         double d = 3.14;
         int x = static_cast<int>(d);  // explicit cast, truncates to 3
     Dangers of implicit: narrowing (data loss), sign issues.
     In class design, mark constructors explicit to prevent unintended implicit
     conversions:
         explicit MyClass(int x) { }  // prevents MyClass obj = 5;

Q32. What is integer promotion in C?
     Asked at: Sasken, Embedded roles
A:   Integer promotion is the automatic conversion of small integer types
     (char, short, bool) to int (or unsigned int) before arithmetic operations.
     This happens because CPUs work most efficiently with int-sized operands.
     Example:
         char a = 100, b = 200;
         int result = a + b;  // a and b are promoted to int before adding
     Without promotion, char arithmetic could overflow unpredictably.
     This means: sizeof('A') is 4 (int), not 1 (char) in C++.

Q33. What is the difference between signed and unsigned arithmetic?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, Samsung, Sasken
A:   Signed arithmetic: numbers can be positive or negative. Overflow is
     UNDEFINED BEHAVIOR (compilers assume it never happens for optimization).
     Unsigned arithmetic: numbers are always non-negative. Overflow WRAPS
     AROUND modulo 2^N — this is DEFINED behavior.
         unsigned char x = 255;
         x++;  // wraps to 0 (defined)
         signed char y = 127;
         y++;  // undefined behavior (in practice wraps to -128 on most systems)
     In bit manipulation, always prefer unsigned to avoid UB.

Q34. What happens when you compare signed and unsigned integers?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, Sasken, HFT firms
A:   This is a DANGEROUS implicit conversion! The signed integer is converted
     to unsigned before comparison.
     Example:
         int x = -1;
         unsigned int y = 1;
         if (x < y) cout << "x is smaller";  // DOES NOT PRINT!
     Because -1 as unsigned int becomes 4294967295 (2^32 - 1), which is > 1.
     This is a notorious source of bugs in C/C++.
     Fix: always cast explicitly or use same signedness:
         if ((unsigned int)x < y)  // or redesign to avoid mixing

Q35. What is narrowing conversion? How does C++11 handle it?
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro, Google, Atlassian
A:   Narrowing conversion is when a value is converted to a type that cannot
     represent all values of the original type, potentially losing data.
     Examples: double → int (decimal truncation), int → char (range loss),
               long long → int (large values truncated)
     C++11 {} uniform initialization FORBIDS narrowing:
         int x = 3.14;   // OK (C-style): x = 3, silently truncates
         int x{3.14};    // ERROR: narrowing conversion not allowed
     This catches data loss bugs at COMPILE TIME rather than silently at runtime.

Q36. What is std::numeric_limits? When would you use it?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, Goldman Sachs, Quant roles
A:   std::numeric_limits<T> (from <limits>) provides compile-time constants
     for the properties of arithmetic types.
     Common uses:
         numeric_limits<int>::max()      // 2147483647
         numeric_limits<int>::min()      // -2147483648
         numeric_limits<double>::infinity()
         numeric_limits<float>::epsilon()  // smallest difference from 1.0
     Use cases:
     - Initialize min/max trackers: int maxSoFar = numeric_limits<int>::min();
     - Overflow checks
     - Comparing floats with precision awareness
     Preferred over magic numbers like INT_MAX or FLT_EPSILON.

Q37. What is NaN and Inf in floating point? How do you check for them?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, ICICI Securities, Quant roles
A:   NaN (Not a Number): result of invalid operations like 0.0/0.0 or sqrt(-1).
     NaN is UNORDERED — it is not equal to anything, including ITSELF.
         double x = 0.0 / 0.0;
         cout << (x == x);  // prints 0 (false)! — NaN property
     Inf (Infinity): result of overflow like 1.0/0.0.
         double y = 1.0 / 0.0;  // positive infinity
     Checking (from <cmath>):
         std::isnan(x)   // true if x is NaN
         std::isinf(y)   // true if y is +Inf or -Inf
         std::isfinite(z) // true if z is neither NaN nor Inf
     NEVER check with ==: if (x == NaN) will always be false!

Q38. What is the difference between float and double precision?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, Edelweiss, Quant roles
A:   float  — 32-bit IEEE 754, ~7 significant decimal digits, range ±3.4×10^38
     double — 64-bit IEEE 754, ~15-16 significant decimal digits, range ±1.8×10^308
     Example of precision difference:
         float  f = 1.0f / 3.0f;  // ~0.3333333 (7 digits)
         double d = 1.0 / 3.0;    // ~0.333333333333333 (15 digits)
     Use double by default for scientific computing. Use float only when memory
     or GPU performance (SIMD vectorization) matters.

Q39. What is epsilon comparison for floats? Why not use == for floats?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, Goldman Sachs, Quant roles
A:   Floating-point numbers have limited binary precision. Operations like
     0.1 + 0.2 give 0.30000000000000004, NOT exactly 0.3.
     So: if (0.1 + 0.2 == 0.3) is FALSE in C++!
     Fix — use epsilon comparison:
         bool equal = fabs(a - b) < 1e-9;  // for double
         bool equal = fabs(a - b) < 1e-6f; // for float
     For values of varying magnitude, use RELATIVE epsilon:
         bool equal = fabs(a - b) < 1e-9 * max(fabs(a), fabs(b));
     Epsilon (std::numeric_limits<double>::epsilon()) is the smallest double
     such that 1.0 + epsilon != 1.0.

Q40. What is endianness? What is little-endian vs big-endian?
     Asked at: Sasken, Samsung, Networking roles
A:   Endianness refers to the ORDER in which bytes of a multi-byte value are
     stored in memory.
     Little-endian: LEAST significant byte stored FIRST (lowest address)
         0x12345678 stored as: 78 56 34 12
         Used by: x86, x86-64 (Intel, AMD — most modern CPUs)
     Big-endian: MOST significant byte stored FIRST
         0x12345678 stored as: 12 34 56 78
         Used by: network protocols (TCP/IP), some RISC architectures
     Why it matters: network byte order is big-endian; use htons()/htonl()
     to convert when writing portable network code.

Q41. How do you check endianness of a machine in C?
     Asked at: Sasken, Samsung
A:   Classic trick using a union or pointer cast:
     Method 1 (union):
         union { int i; char c; } u;
         u.i = 1;
         if (u.c == 1) cout << "little-endian";
         else cout << "big-endian";
     Method 2 (pointer cast):
         int x = 1;
         char* p = (char*)&x;
         if (*p == 1) cout << "little-endian"; // LSB is at lowest address
     Explanation: if the first byte (lowest address) holds the value 1 (LSB),
     it's little-endian. If it holds 0, it's big-endian.

