Q42. What is the difference between signed and unsigned right shift?
     Asked at: Samsung, Dolat Capital, Sasken
A:   Unsigned right shift (>> on unsigned type): always fills vacated bits
     from the left with 0. Called LOGICAL shift.
         unsigned int x = 0x80000000;
         x >> 1;  // becomes 0x40000000 (fills with 0)
     Signed right shift (>> on signed int): IMPLEMENTATION-DEFINED in C++
     standard. On most compilers (GCC, Clang, MSVC), it performs ARITHMETIC
     shift — fills with the SIGN BIT (preserving sign).
         int x = -8;
         x >> 1;  // -4 on most systems (arithmetic shift)
     Recommendation: for bit manipulation, always use UNSIGNED types to
     get predictable logical shift behavior.

Q43. What is type promotion in C++? What happens when you add char + int?
     Asked at: TCS, L&T Infotech, Wipro
A:   Type promotion is the automatic conversion of smaller types to larger types
     before arithmetic operations to avoid overflow and match CPU word size.
     Rule — "Usual Arithmetic Conversions":
     char + int   → both promoted to int → result is int
     int + float  → int promoted to float → result is float
     float + double → float promoted to double → result is double
     Example:
         char c = 'A';  // ASCII 65
         int x = c + 1;  // c promoted to int (65), result is 66 ('B')
     This is why sizeof('A') is 4 (int after promotion) in C, but 1 in C++.

Q44. What is the difference between NaN and Infinity in floating point?
     How do you check for them in C++?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, HFT firms
A:   NaN (Not a Number):
     - Produced by: 0.0/0.0, sqrt(-1.0), log(-1.0), 0.0 * Inf
     - UNORDERED: NaN != NaN is TRUE (the only value not equal to itself)
     - Any arithmetic involving NaN produces NaN (propagates)
     Infinity:
     - Produced by: 1.0/0.0 (positive), -1.0/0.0 (negative), overflow
     - Ordered: Inf > any finite value, -Inf < any finite value
     - Inf + Inf = Inf, Inf - Inf = NaN, 1.0 / Inf = 0.0
     Checks (#include <cmath>):
         std::isnan(x)    — true if NaN
         std::isinf(x)    — true if +Inf or -Inf
         std::isfinite(x) — true if neither NaN nor Inf

Q45. What does the comma operator do in C++? Give a tricky example.
     Asked at: Google, Zoho
A:   The comma operator evaluates both operands LEFT TO RIGHT and returns
     the value of the RIGHTMOST operand. Has the lowest precedence.
     Example:
         int x = (3, 5);      // x = 5 (3 is evaluated but discarded)
         int a = 1, b = 2;
         int c = (a++, b++);  // evaluates a++, then b++, c = 2 (old b)
     Tricky: int arr[5]; int i = (arr[1]=10, arr[2]=20, 3); // i = 3
     Common use: in for loop initializers to initialize multiple variables:
         for (int i=0, j=10; i < j; i++, j--) { }  // the i++, j-- uses comma
     The comma in function arguments is NOT the comma operator.

Q46. What is integral promotion? What is the "usual arithmetic conversion"?
     Asked at: Sasken, Samsung
A:   Integral Promotion: char, short, bool are promoted to int (or unsigned int)
     before any arithmetic. This happens automatically by the compiler.
     "Usual Arithmetic Conversion" (UAC): when an operation involves two
     different arithmetic types, both are converted to a COMMON TYPE:
     1. If either is long double → both become long double
     2. Else if either is double → both become double
     3. Else if either is float → both become float
     4. Else: apply integral promotion, then:
        - If same type → done
        - If same signedness → smaller type converted to larger
        - Otherwise → complex signed/unsigned rules apply
     Key takeaway: arithmetic in C++ always happens at int size or larger.

Q47. What is the difference between char, signed char, and unsigned char?
     Are they all distinct types?
     Asked at: Samsung, Sasken, Embedded roles
A:   YES — they are THREE DISTINCT types in C++, even though they all use 1 byte.
     char          — signedness is IMPLEMENTATION-DEFINED (signed on most
                     x86 systems, unsigned on some ARM systems)
     signed char   — explicitly signed, range: -128 to +127
     unsigned char — explicitly unsigned, range: 0 to 255
     This matters for:
     - Portable character processing: don't assume char is signed
     - Bit manipulation: use unsigned char to avoid sign extension
     - Function overloading: char, signed char, unsigned char can have
       different overloads
     Rule: for raw byte manipulation, always use unsigned char or std::byte.

Q48. Can you have a reference to a reference in C++? What about pointer to reference?
     Asked at: Advanced C++ roles, Google
A:   Reference to reference: NOT DIRECTLY POSSIBLE in C++.
         int& & rr = x;  // ILLEGAL — compiler error
     However, REFERENCE COLLAPSING rules in templates allow T& where T is
     already a reference — used internally for perfect forwarding.
     Pointer to reference: also NOT ALLOWED.
         int& x = y;
         int& * p = &x;  // ILLEGAL — cannot have a pointer to a reference
     Reasoning: a reference is not an object — it has no address.
     You CAN have a reference to a pointer:
         int* p = &x;
         int*& rp = p;  // reference to pointer — valid

Q49. What is std::numeric_limits<int>::max() and when would you use it?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Competitive programming roles
A:   std::numeric_limits<int>::max() returns the maximum value an int can hold:
     2147483647 (2^31 - 1).
     Use cases:
     - Initialize "minimum so far" trackers:
         int minSoFar = numeric_limits<int>::max();
     - Check if adding two numbers would overflow:
         if (a > numeric_limits<int>::max() - b) { /* overflow */ }
     - As sentinel/infinity values in graph algorithms (Dijkstra, BFS)
     Better than using INT_MAX (#include <climits>) because it works
     generically with templates: numeric_limits<T>::max() for any type T.

Q50. What is the difference between {}-initialization and ()-initialization?
     What is narrowing conversion?
     Asked at: Google, Atlassian, Modern C++ roles
A:   ()-initialization: allows narrowing (data loss without error).
         int x(3.14);   // OK: x = 3, decimal silently truncated
         int x(300);    // OK even if assigning to char later
     {}-initialization (uniform init, C++11): FORBIDS narrowing — compile error.
         int x{3.14};   // ERROR: narrowing from double to int
         int x{300};    // OK (300 fits in int)
         char c{300};   // ERROR: 300 doesn't fit in char (-128..127)
     Narrowing conversion: any conversion where the target type cannot represent
     all values of the source type.
     Recommendation: prefer {} for initialization — catches data loss at compile
     time. Use () only when calling constructors with deliberate type coercion.

Q51. What is a magic number? (Covered in Q20 — same question, different bank)
     Additional point: In embedded/systems programming, magic numbers
     also refer to file format identifiers (e.g., ELF files start with 0x7F454C46).
     These are acceptable magic numbers with documented purposes.


