Q52. What is the difference between if-else and switch?
     When would you prefer switch over if-else?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Zoho, Infosys
A:   if-else: works with ANY condition — ranges, floats, complex booleans,
              string comparisons (via ==), runtime-computed values.
     switch:  works ONLY with integral types (int, char, enum) and requires
              COMPILE-TIME CONSTANT case labels. Cannot use float or string.
     Prefer switch when:
     - Many discrete integer/enum cases (cleaner, more readable)
     - Compiler may optimize as a jump table (O(1) lookup vs O(N) if-else chain)
     Prefer if-else when:
     - Condition involves ranges: if (x > 0 && x < 100)
     - Conditions involve floats, strings, or complex logic
     - Cases are not known at compile time

Q53. What is fall-through in switch? How do you prevent it?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys
A:   Fall-through means execution "falls" into the NEXT case without stopping,
     because break was omitted.
         switch(x) {
             case 1: cout << "one";  // no break — falls through!
             case 2: cout << "two"; break;
         }
     If x == 1: prints "onetwo" (both cases execute).
     Prevention: always add break; at the end of each case.
     Intentional fall-through: useful when multiple cases share the same action:
         case 'a': case 'e': case 'i': case 'o': case 'u':
             cout << "vowel"; break;
     C++17: use [[fallthrough]] attribute to document intent and silence warnings.

Q54. Can switch work with strings in C++? Why or why not?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Zoho
A:   NO. switch requires COMPILE-TIME INTEGER CONSTANTS for case labels.
     std::string is a class object, not an integral type — it has no integer
     value at compile time that can be used as a case label.
     Alternative: use if-else with string ==, or use an unordered_map to map
     strings to integers and switch on the integer:
         unordered_map<string, int> mp = {{"add",1}, {"sub",2}};
         switch(mp[input]) {
             case 1: ... case 2: ...
         }

Q55. What is a ternary operator? How is it different from if-else?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Capgemini
A:   Ternary (conditional) operator: condition ? value_if_true : value_if_false
         int max = (a > b) ? a : b;
     Differences from if-else:
     - Ternary is an EXPRESSION (returns a value), if-else is a STATEMENT
     - Ternary can be used inline: cout << (x > 0 ? "pos" : "neg");
     - Ternary cannot execute multiple statements in each branch
     - Both branches of ternary must have compatible types
     Nested ternary is possible but hard to read — avoid beyond one level.

Q56. What is short-circuit evaluation? How does it affect conditionals?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Zoho
A:   && (AND): if left is FALSE → right side is NOT evaluated (result is false)
     || (OR):  if left is TRUE  → right side is NOT evaluated (result is true)
     Safety use:
         if (ptr != nullptr && ptr->data > 0)  // ptr never dereferenced if null
         if (index >= 0 && index < n && arr[index] == x)  // safe bounds check
     Side-effect trap:
         if (++i > 0 || ++j > 0)  // j may NOT be incremented!
         if (a() && b())          // b() may not be called if a() returns false
     Always be aware of short-circuiting when function calls with side effects
     appear in conditions.

Q57. What is the difference between = and == in a conditional? Why is if(x=5) a bug?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys
A:   = is ASSIGNMENT: if (x = 5) assigns 5 to x, then evaluates x as the
     condition. Since 5 is non-zero, this is ALWAYS TRUE — a logical bug.
     == is EQUALITY CHECK: if (x == 5) tests whether x equals 5.
     Defense techniques:
     1. Enable compiler warning: -Wall catches this
     2. Yoda condition: if (5 == x) — if you write if (5 = x) → compile error
     3. Use === in languages that support strict equality
     This is one of the most common beginner bugs in C/C++.

Q58. Can you use a float or double in a switch statement? Why?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro
A:   NO. switch requires an INTEGRAL type (int, char, short, long, enum, bool).
     Floats and doubles are NOT integral — they cannot be used as switch
     expression or case labels.
     Reason: case values must be compile-time integer constants for the compiler
     to generate a jump table or comparison chain. Floating-point equality is
     unreliable due to precision issues, so the language forbids this.
     Alternative: convert to int (losing precision) or use if-else with
     epsilon comparisons for float ranges.

Q59. What happens if you forget break in a switch case?
     What is intentional fall-through and when is it useful?
     Asked at: TCS, Zoho, Amazon
A:   Without break: execution continues into the NEXT case block, regardless of
     whether its value matches.
         case 1: doOne();  // falls through to case 2!
         case 2: doTwo(); break;
     If x == 1: both doOne() and doTwo() are called — usually a bug.
     Intentional fall-through uses:
     1. Multiple values, same action:
            case 'A': case 'B': case 'C': handleABC(); break;
     2. Staggered actions (rare):
            case 3: doExtraForThree();  // intentionally falls through
            case 2: doForTwoAndThree(); break;
     In C++17, add [[fallthrough]]; to document intent and suppress warnings.

Q60. What is a dangling else problem? How does C++ resolve it?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Adobe
A:   When nested ifs appear without braces, it's ambiguous which if the else
     pairs with:
         if (a)
             if (b) cout << "both";
         else cout << "?";  // which if does this belong to?
     C++ Rule: else binds to the NEAREST preceding unmatched if.
     So the else pairs with if(b), NOT if(a).
     If a=false, nothing prints. If a=true and b=false, "?" prints.
     Fix: ALWAYS use braces {} to make intent explicit:
         if (a) {
             if (b) cout << "both";
         } else cout << "not a";

