Q61. What is the difference between for, while, and do-while loops?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys, Zoho
A:   for loop: best when iterations are KNOWN upfront; compact init/check/update
         for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) { }
     while loop: best when iterations depend on a CONDITION checked before entry.
         while (condition) { }  // might execute 0 times
     do-while loop: condition checked AFTER body — executes AT LEAST ONCE.
         do { } while (condition);
     When to use do-while:
     - Input validation: keep asking until valid input received
         do { cin >> x; } while (x < 0);  // execute first, validate after
     Rule of thumb: for = known count, while = unknown count (check first),
     do-while = must run at least once.

Q62. What is the difference between break and continue?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys, Capgemini
A:   break:    exits the INNERMOST loop or switch entirely and continues
               after the loop/switch.
     continue: skips the REST of the CURRENT ITERATION and jumps to the
               next iteration (for: goes to update step; while/do-while:
               re-evaluates condition).
     Example:
         for (int i = 0; i < 6; i++) {
             if (i == 2) continue;  // skip i=2
             if (i == 5) break;     // stop at i=5
             cout << i << " ";
         }
     Output: 0 1 3 4    (2 skipped, stops before 5)

Q63. What is an infinite loop? How do you create one intentionally? How to exit?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Amazon
A:   An infinite loop has no natural termination — it runs until externally
     interrupted.
     Creation:
         while (true) { }    // most readable
         for (;;) { }        // common C idiom
         while (1) { }       // C-style
     Exit methods:
     - break inside the loop (condition-based exit)
     - return (exits the entire function)
     - throw an exception
     - std::exit(0) or std::terminate()
     Use cases: event loops, server listener loops, embedded system main loops,
     game loops, REPL environments.

Q64. Why does do-while execute at least once?
     Give a real use-case where do-while is the right choice.
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys
A:   In a do-while loop, the BODY executes FIRST, and the condition is checked
     AFTER each iteration. So the first execution is unconditional.
         do {
             cout << "Enter password: ";
             cin >> password;
         } while (password != correct);
     Real use cases:
     - Input validation (must read input at least once before checking)
     - Menu systems (must display menu at least once)
     - Retry-on-failure logic (attempt the action, then check success)
     Compare: while(condition) might never execute if condition is false initially;
     do-while always runs the body at least once.

Q65. What is the range-based for loop? How does it work internally?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Google
A:   Introduced in C++11 for clean container iteration:
         for (int x : vec) { cout << x; }
         for (auto& x : vec) { x *= 2; }  // modify via reference
     Internal expansion by compiler:
         auto __begin = vec.begin();
         auto __end = vec.end();
         for (; __begin != __end; ++__begin) {
             int x = *__begin;
             // loop body
         }
     Requirements: the object must provide begin() and end() methods (or
     free functions std::begin()/std::end()). Works with arrays, STL containers,
     strings, and custom types implementing the iterator interface.

Q66. What is the time complexity of a single loop? A nested loop?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Amazon
A:   Single loop over N elements: O(N)
         for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) { O(1) work }  → O(N)
     Nested loop (two levels over N): O(N^2)
         for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
             for (int j = 0; j < n; j++) { O(1) work }  → O(N^2)
     Nested with different bounds:
         for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
             for (int j = i; j < n; j++) { }  → O(N^2 / 2) = O(N^2)
     Logarithmic inner: O(N log N):
         for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
             for (int j = 1; j < n; j *= 2) { }  → O(N log N)
     Rule: multiply complexities of nested independent loops.

Q67. What is loop invariant? How does it help prove loop correctness?
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Google
A:   A loop invariant is a property/condition that holds TRUE before the loop,
     at the start of EVERY iteration, and after the loop terminates.
     Proof structure (3 steps):
     1. Initialization: show the invariant is true BEFORE the first iteration
     2. Maintenance: show that if it's true at iteration start, it's true after
     3. Termination: at loop end, invariant + termination condition → correctness
     Example — finding max in array:
         Invariant: "max contains the maximum of arr[0..i-1]"
         Before loop (i=0): trivially true (empty range)
         Maintenance: if max holds for arr[0..i-1], after checking arr[i],
         max holds for arr[0..i]
         Termination: at i=n, max is maximum of arr[0..n-1] ✓
     Loop invariants form the basis of formal algorithm correctness proofs.

Q68. What is the difference between pre-increment (++i) and post-increment (i++)
     in a loop condition? Does it matter for performance?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Amazon, Adobe
A:   In simple loop counters:
         for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)  vs  for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
     For PRIMITIVES (int, char, etc.): NO performance difference — modern
     compilers optimize both identically at -O1 or higher.
     For ITERATORS and OBJECTS: ++i is PREFERRED because:
     - i++ creates a TEMPORARY COPY of the old value (needs extra object)
     - ++i increments in-place and returns a reference — no copy needed
     - For complex iterators (like std::list::iterator), this copy is non-trivial
     As a best practice, always write ++i in loops — communicates intent and
     is never slower.

Q69. Can you modify the loop variable inside a for loop body? What are the risks?
     Asked at: TCS, Wipro
A:   YES, you CAN — C++ allows it. But it's risky and usually a bad practice.
     Example (dangerous):
         for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
             if (condition) i += 2;  // skips iterations!
         }
     Risks:
     - Off-by-one errors: hard to reason about which iterations execute
     - Skipping or double-processing elements
     - Infinite loops if you accidentally reset i to 0
     - Confusing to readers (loop update step + body modification)
     Better alternatives: use while loop (makes variable control explicit),
     or use flags/counters as separate variables inside the loop.

Q70. What is an off-by-one error? Give an example in a loop.
     Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Adobe
A:   Off-by-one (OOB) errors occur when a loop runs one time too many or too
     few — usually from wrong boundary condition (< vs <=).
     Example 1 — out-of-bounds:
         int arr[5] = {1,2,3,4,5};
         for (int i = 0; i <= 5; i++)  // WRONG: i=5 is out of bounds
         for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++)   // CORRECT
     Example 2 — missing first element:
         for (int i = 1; i < n; i++)   // misses arr[0]
     Example 3 — string null terminator:
         char s[10] = "hello";
         for (int i = 0; i <= 10; i++) s[i] = 0;  // WRONG: i=10 is UB
     Test strategy: always check loop behavior with n=0 and n=1 as edge cases.

