Q71. What is branch prediction? How can unpredictable branches hurt performance?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, HFT firms, Samsung, Sasken
A:   Modern CPUs use BRANCH PREDICTION to guess which path (if or else) will
     execute and pre-load instructions speculatively. If the prediction is WRONG:
     1. The speculatively executed instructions are discarded
     2. The pipeline is flushed (~15-20 cycles wasted)
     For PREDICTABLE branches (e.g., always-false bounds checks), the predictor
     achieves near-100% accuracy — minimal cost.
     For RANDOM/UNPREDICTABLE branches (e.g., checking unsorted random data),
     misprediction rate can be ~50% — massive performance hit in tight loops.
     Fix: sort data to make branches predictable; use branchless techniques:
         // Branchless max (no branch):
         int max = a - ((a - b) & ((a - b) >> 31));

Q72. What is the likely/unlikely hint in GCC? (__builtin_expect)
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, HFT firms
A:   __builtin_expect tells the compiler which branch is the "hot" (likely)
     path, so it places that path inline and puts the cold path in a jump.
         if (__builtin_expect(ptr == nullptr, 0)) {  // 0 = unlikely (false)
             handleError();
         }
         if (__builtin_expect(x > 0, 1)) {  // 1 = likely (true)
             doNormalPath();
         }
     C++20 introduced standard attributes: [[likely]] and [[unlikely]]:
         if (x > 0) [[likely]] { doNormalPath(); }
     Benefits: better instruction cache usage, CPU pipeline optimization.
     Use when you KNOW from profiling that one branch dominates (>95% of cases).

Q73. What is loop unrolling? When does the compiler do it automatically?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, Sasken, Samsung
A:   Loop unrolling reduces loop overhead by expanding multiple iterations
     into sequential code, reducing branch checks and enabling better
     instruction-level parallelism.
     Manual unroll:
         // Original:  for (int i=0; i<4; i++) a[i] *= 2;
         // Unrolled:  a[0]*=2; a[1]*=2; a[2]*=2; a[3]*=2;
     Benefits:
     - Fewer loop condition checks and branches
     - CPU can execute multiple operations in parallel (superscalar)
     - Enables auto-vectorization (SIMD instructions)
     Automatic: compilers unroll with -O2 or -O3 when:
     - Loop count is small and known at compile time
     - Loop body is simple
     - No dependencies between iterations
     Downside: increases code size (icache pressure) — don't always unroll.


