Q84. What is a function pointer? Show the syntax.
     Asked at: L&T Infotech, Persistent, Sasken
A:   A function pointer stores the ADDRESS of a function and allows calling it
     indirectly.
     Syntax:
         return_type (*pointer_name)(param_types);
         int (*fp)(int, int);      // pointer to function (int, int) → int
         fp = &add;                // assign (& is optional)
         int result = fp(3, 4);    // call via pointer
         int result = (*fp)(3, 4); // also valid
     Use cases: callbacks, dispatch tables, strategy pattern.
     Cleaner alternative: use typedef or using:
         using BinaryOp = int(*)(int, int);
         BinaryOp op = add;

Q85. What is a callback function? Give a real-world example.
     Asked at: L&T Infotech, Persistent, Nagarro
A:   A callback is a function PASSED AS AN ARGUMENT to another function,
     to be called at a later time or when a certain event occurs.
     Example — qsort with comparator:
         int compare(const void* a, const void* b) {
             return *(int*)a - *(int*)b;
         }
         qsort(arr, n, sizeof(int), compare);  // compare is the callback
     STL example:
         sort(v.begin(), v.end(), [](int a, int b){ return a > b; });
     Real-world: button click handlers in GUIs, file I/O completion in async
     systems, HTTP response handlers, event listeners.
     Modern C++: use std::function or templates instead of raw function pointers
     for type-safe, flexible callbacks.

Q86. What is std::function? How is it different from a raw function pointer?
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro, Adobe
A:   std::function<ReturnType(ParamTypes...)> is a general-purpose callable
     wrapper that can hold functions, lambdas, functors, and bound expressions.
         std::function<int(int,int)> op;
         op = add;                          // regular function
         op = [](int a, int b){ return a+b; }; // lambda
         op = std::bind(multiply, _1, _2);  // bound function
     Differences from raw function pointer:
     - Function pointer: only holds plain functions and C-compatible function ptrs
     - std::function: holds ANY callable — functions, lambdas, functors, bind
     - std::function has slight overhead (type erasure, heap allocation for large
       callables)
     - std::function is safer, more flexible, and idiomatic modern C++
     Use raw function pointer only in performance-critical or C-interop code.

Q87. What is std::bind? Give an example.
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro
A:   std::bind creates a new callable by binding some (or all) arguments of
     an existing function, producing a partial application.
         #include <functional>
         int add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }
         auto add5 = std::bind(add, std::placeholders::_1, 5);
         cout << add5(3);  // calls add(3, 5) → 8
     Use cases: creating callbacks with pre-filled arguments, adapting function
     signatures for algorithms, member function binding:
         auto f = std::bind(&MyClass::method, &obj, _1);
     Modern C++: prefer LAMBDAS over std::bind — clearer, faster (no overhead):
         auto add5 = [](int a) { return add(a, 5); };

Q88. What is a functor (function object)? Why use it over a regular function?
     Asked at: L&T Infotech, Persistent, Sasken
A:   A functor is a class/struct that overloads operator(), making instances
     CALLABLE like functions.
         struct Multiplier {
             int factor;
             Multiplier(int f) : factor(f) {}
             int operator()(int x) const { return x * factor; }
         };
         Multiplier triple(3);
         cout << triple(5);  // 15
         transform(v.begin(), v.end(), v.begin(), Multiplier(2));
     Advantages over plain functions:
     - Can maintain STATE between calls (unlike stateless functions)
     - Can be INLINED by compiler more easily than function pointers
     - Can be templated for generic algorithms
     - More composable and testable than global functions
     Modern C++: lambdas are essentially anonymous functors — prefer them for
     inline use; use named functors when state or reuse across files is needed.

Q89. What is a lambda? How does the capture clause work?
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro, Adobe, Amazon
A:   A lambda is an ANONYMOUS inline function object (C++11).
     Syntax: [capture](params) -> return_type { body }
     Capture clause — controls which outer variables the lambda can access:
         []        — captures NOTHING (can only use params and globals)
         [=]       — captures all locals by VALUE (copy)
         [&]       — captures all locals by REFERENCE
         [x]       — captures x by value
         [&x]      — captures x by reference
         [=, &y]   — all by value, but y by reference
         [this]    — captures the current object pointer
     Example:
         int mul = 3;
         auto triple = [mul](int x) { return x * mul; };
         cout << triple(5);  // 15
     Lambdas are syntactic sugar for compiler-generated functors.
     Return type is deduced if omitted. Mutable lambdas allow modifying by-value captures.

Q90. What is the difference between [=] and [&] in lambda capture?
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro
A:   [=] — captures ALL used outer variables BY VALUE (copy at time of lambda
            creation). Lambda has its own private copy.
         int x = 5;
         auto f = [=]() { return x; };
         x = 100;
         cout << f();  // prints 5 (captured the old value)
     [&] — captures ALL used outer variables BY REFERENCE (accesses the
            original variable directly).
         int x = 5;
         auto g = [&]() { return x; };
         x = 100;
         cout << g();  // prints 100 (uses current value of x)
     DANGER with [&]: if the lambda outlives the captured variable (e.g., stored
     in a callback that runs after the variable is destroyed), this is DANGLING
     REFERENCE — undefined behavior.
     Rule: prefer [=] for safety when lambda escapes the current scope;
     use [&] only for lambdas that execute within the same scope.

Q91. Can a lambda be recursive? How do you achieve it?
     Asked at: Advanced C++ roles
A:   A lambda cannot directly call itself by name because it has no name.
     Solutions:
     1. Use std::function (slight overhead):
            std::function<int(int)> fib = [&](int n) -> int {
                if (n <= 1) return n;
                return fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);  // captures fib by reference
            };
     2. Pass lambda to itself as parameter (template trick):
            auto fib = [](auto& self, int n) -> int {
                if (n <= 1) return n;
                return self(self, n-1) + self(self, n-2);
            };
            cout << fib(fib, 10);
     3. C++23: deducing this (cleanest approach, not yet widely available)
     Option 1 is most commonly seen in interviews.

Q92. What is memoization using C++ lambdas?
     Asked at: Dolat Capital, Goldman Sachs
A:   Memoization caches the results of function calls so repeated calls with
     the same arguments return the cached result instead of recomputing.
     Lambda + map approach:
         unordered_map<int, long long> memo;
         std::function<long long(int)> fib = [&](int n) -> long long {
             if (n <= 1) return n;
             auto it = memo.find(n);
             if (it != memo.end()) return it->second;
             return memo[n] = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
         };
     This turns naive O(2^N) Fibonacci into O(N) time, O(N) space.
     Used for: DP problems, expensive repeated computations, caching API calls.

Q93. What is the return type deduction for functions in C++14?
     Asked at: Persistent, Nagarro
A:   C++14 allows functions to use auto as return type, and the compiler
     DEDUCES the actual return type from the return statement.
         auto add(int a, int b) { return a + b; }  // deduced as int
         auto makeList() { return std::vector<int>{1,2,3}; } // deduced as vector<int>
     Rules:
     - All return statements must return the same type
     - For recursive functions, at least one return statement must be deducible
       before the recursive call
     Decltype-trailing return type (C++11):
         auto add(int a, int b) -> decltype(a + b) { return a + b; }
     Use when: the return type is complex/verbose to write explicitly, or for
     generic functions where the return type depends on template parameters.

Q94. What is the difference between a macro and an inline function?
     Asked at: L&T Infotech, Persistent, Nagarro
A:   Macro (#define): textual substitution at PREPROCESSING stage, before compilation.
         #define SQUARE(x) ((x)*(x))
         SQUARE(1+2)  → ((1+2)*(1+2)) = 9  // needs extra parens!
     Problems with macros:
     - No type checking — any type accepted, errors only at expansion
     - Scope-unaware — bypasses C++ scoping rules
     - Tricky side effects: SQUARE(i++) → ((i++)*(i++)) — UB!
     - No debugger support (macros don't appear in symbol tables)
     Inline function:
     - Full C++ type safety and scope rules
     - Compiler decides whether to actually inline
     - No side-effect issues — argument evaluated ONCE
     Rule: ALWAYS prefer inline functions (or constexpr) over macros in C++.
     Only use macros for things that truly require preprocessor features
     (#include guards, conditional compilation).

Q95. What is the difference between deep copy and shallow copy?
     Asked at: Zoho, TCS, Wipro, Persistent
A:   Shallow copy: copies the values of member variables, including pointers
     — both original and copy point to the SAME heap memory.
         Object a; Object b = a;  // default copy constructor = shallow
     Problem: if both objects try to delete the same pointer → double-free UB.
     Deep copy: allocates NEW memory and copies the CONTENTS pointed to, so
     original and copy own INDEPENDENT copies of the data.
     When it matters: when passing objects with raw pointers to functions —
     the function receives a copy of the object, and what "copy" means depends
     on whether deep/shallow copy is used.
     In modern C++: use RAII (smart pointers, std::vector, std::string) to
     avoid manual memory management — the correct deep copy is automatic.

