Q101. What is the time complexity of accessing, inserting, and deleting in array?
      Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Infosys, Amazon
A:    Access by index:              O(1)  — address = base + i * element_size
      Search (unsorted):            O(N)  — linear scan
      Search (sorted, binary):      O(log N)
      Insertion at end (vector):    O(1) amortized
      Insertion at beginning/mid:   O(N)  — all elements after must shift right
      Deletion at end:              O(1)
      Deletion at beginning/mid:    O(N)  — elements must shift left
      Arrays excel at RANDOM ACCESS; they are poor for frequent middle insert/delete.
      For frequent insertions/deletions in middle → use linked list or deque.

Q102. What is the difference between static and dynamic arrays?
      Asked at: TCS, Wipro, Amazon, Flipkart
A:    Static array: size fixed at COMPILE TIME, allocated on STACK.
          int arr[100];      // must be compile-time constant
          int arr[n];        // Variable-Length Array — not standard C++, compiler extension
      Limitations: cannot resize, limited stack memory.
      Dynamic array: size at RUNTIME, allocated on HEAP.
          int* arr = new int[n];   // n is a runtime variable
          delete[] arr;            // must free manually
      std::vector: the preferred C++ dynamic array — handles memory automatically,
      grows as needed, provides bounds checking (.at()), iterators, and algorithms.
      Always prefer vector<int> over raw dynamic arrays in modern C++.

Q103. How does vector<int> work internally? What happens when it resizes?
      Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Google, Flipkart
A:    A vector internally manages: begin pointer, size (used elements), capacity.
      When push_back is called and size == capacity:
      1. Allocate new array of size capacity * 2 (typically)
      2. Move/copy all elements to new array
      3. Destroy old array
      4. Update pointers
      This resize is O(N) but happens RARELY (exponential growth intervals).
      The AMORTIZED cost per push_back is O(1) (total copies = 2N for N pushes).
      Key operations: reserve(n) — pre-allocates capacity without changing size
      (avoids repeated resizing when N is known). shrink_to_fit() releases excess.
      Important: resize/push_back CAN INVALIDATE iterators, pointers, references
      to elements (because the underlying array may move to a new address).

Q104. What is cache locality? Why are arrays cache-friendly?
      Asked at: Dolat Capital, HFT firms, Samsung, Google
A:    CPUs cache recently accessed memory in L1/L2/L3 cache. A cache LINE
      (typically 64 bytes) is loaded at once. If the next access is nearby in
      memory, it's a CACHE HIT (fast, ~1-4 cycles).
      Arrays: elements stored CONTIGUOUSLY. Iterating sequentially loads each
      cache line once and uses all elements in it → near-100% cache hit rate
      (spatial locality).
      Linked lists: nodes scattered at random heap addresses. Each dereference
      of a->next likely causes a CACHE MISS (~100-300 cycles for RAM access).
      Real impact: iterating a 10M element array can be 5-10x faster than a
      linked list with same elements due to cache behavior alone.
      In tight loops: struct of arrays (SoA) layout is often more cache-friendly
      than array of structs (AoS) for processing one field at a time.

Q105. What is the difference between array and pointer in C++?
      Asked at: TCS, Wipro, L&T Infotech, Sasken
A:    Key differences:
      - sizeof(arr) on array gives TOTAL size in bytes (e.g., 5*4 = 20 for int[5])
      - sizeof(ptr) on pointer gives pointer size (4 or 8 bytes — address size)
      - Array name decays to pointer to first element in most contexts
          int arr[5]; int* p = arr;  // arr decays to &arr[0]
      - Arrays CANNOT be reassigned (arr = somethingElse is illegal)
      - Pointers are variables and can be reassigned (p = anotherArray)
      - Arrays have compile-time known size; pointers don't carry size info
      Passing array to function: the array DECAYS to a pointer — size is lost!
          void f(int arr[], int n)  // arr is just int*, n needed separately

Q106. What is a 2D array? How is it stored in memory (row-major order)?
      Asked at: Samsung, Sasken, TCS, Wipro
A:    A 2D array is logically a grid (rows × columns) but physically stored
      as a single contiguous block in memory.
      C++ uses ROW-MAJOR ORDER: all elements of row 0 first, then row 1, etc.
          int arr[3][4];
          Memory: arr[0][0], arr[0][1], arr[0][2], arr[0][3],  // row 0
                  arr[1][0], arr[1][1], arr[1][2], arr[1][3],  // row 1
                  arr[2][0], ...                                // row 2
      Address formula: base + (i * cols + j) * sizeof(element)
      Performance implication: iterate ROW by ROW for cache efficiency.
          for(i) for(j) arr[i][j]++;   // CACHE FRIENDLY — sequential access
          for(j) for(i) arr[i][j]++;   // CACHE UNFRIENDLY — column-wise skips

Q107. What is amortized O(1) for vector push_back? Explain the resizing strategy.
      Asked at: Amazon, Microsoft, Flipkart, Swiggy
A:    Individual push_back: O(1) normally, but O(N) when resizing occurs.
      Amortized analysis considers the AVERAGE cost over a sequence of N operations.
      With DOUBLING strategy (capacity doubles on each resize):
      - Resizes occur at sizes: 1, 2, 4, 8, ..., N (total: log N resizes)
      - Elements copied at each resize: 1, 2, 4, ..., N/2
      - Total copies: 1+2+4+...+N/2 = N-1 (geometric series)
      - Average copy per push_back: (N-1)/N ≈ 1 = O(1)
      So N push_backs cost O(N) total → O(1) each on average = amortized O(1).
      Contrast: if we grew by 1 each time, N push_backs would cost O(N^2) total.
      The doubling factor (typically 2x or 1.5x) balances time vs wasted space.

Q108. Why is cache performance better for arrays than linked lists?
      Explain spatial locality.
      Asked at: Dolat Capital, HFT firms, Samsung
A:    Spatial locality: if address X is accessed, nearby addresses (X+1, X+2, ...)
      are LIKELY to be accessed soon. CPUs exploit this by loading entire cache
      lines (64 bytes) on each miss.
      Array: elements are at consecutive addresses (index 0, 1, 2, ...). When
      arr[0] is accessed, the CPU loads arr[0] through arr[15] (for int[]) into
      cache. Subsequent accesses to arr[1]-arr[15] are cache HITS (~1 cycle).
      Linked list: each node's next pointer points to a RANDOM heap address.
      Following next requires loading a new cache line for EACH node.
      For a 1M element traversal:
      - Array: ~1M/16 = ~62,500 cache misses
      - Linked list: ~1M cache misses (each node is likely a miss)
      This is why arrays are preferred over linked lists for sequential access,
      even when big-O complexity is the same.

Q109. What is the difference between row-major and column-major order?
      Which does C++ use?
      Asked at: Samsung, Sasken, Numerical computing roles
A:    Row-major order: elements of each ROW are stored consecutively.
      C, C++, Python (NumPy default) use row-major.
      Column-major order: elements of each COLUMN are stored consecutively.
      Fortran, MATLAB, Julia use column-major.
      For matrix arr[R][C]:
      Row-major address of arr[i][j]:    base + (i*C + j) * size
      Column-major address of arr[i][j]: base + (i + j*R) * size
      Performance implication:
      C++ programmers should iterate row-by-row (arr[i][j]) for cache efficiency.
      If interfacing with Fortran/MATLAB (e.g., in numerical computing), be aware
      of the mismatch — matrix transposes may be needed at the boundary.

Q110. What is the complexity of inserting at the beginning of a vector?
      How would you make this faster?
      Asked at: Amazon, Flipkart
A:    O(N): every existing element must shift one position to the right to make
      room at index 0. For a vector of 1M elements, this means 1M moves.
      Ways to make it faster:
      1. std::deque: provides O(1) amortized insertion at BOTH front AND back.
         Trade-off: slightly slower random access than vector (deque uses
         segmented storage, not single contiguous array).
      2. Reverse the problem: if you frequently insert at "beginning" and then
         iterate, insert at END and reverse the iteration or reverse the whole
         container at the end.
      3. Maintain an offset index: treat arr[offset] as the logical first element.
         "Insertion at beginning" increments offset — no shifting needed.
      4. Linked list: O(1) prepend, but poor cache performance for iteration.

Q111. What is a sparse array and how would you implement it efficiently?
      Asked at: Google, Atlassian, Adobe
A:    A sparse array has MOST elements equal to a default value (zero or null).
      Storing all elements in a regular array wastes memory.
      Efficient implementations:
      1. Hash map (unordered_map<int, T>): store only non-default elements.
             unordered_map<int, int> sparse;
             sparse[1000000] = 42;  // only stores this one entry
         O(1) average access, O(K) space where K = number of non-default elements
      2. Sorted vector of (index, value) pairs: good for sparse + ordered access
      3. Compressed Sparse Row (CSR): used in scientific/graph computing
         Stores row_ptr[], col_ind[], values[] arrays compactly
      4. std::map<int, T>: ordered access, O(log K) lookup
      Use case: adjacency matrix for sparse graphs (millions of nodes, few edges),
      spreadsheet cells, image compression, NLP feature vectors.


================================================================================
QUICK REVISION CHEAT SHEET
================================================================================

VARIABLES — KEY RULES:
  - i++ vs ++i: same for primitives; ++i preferred for iterators (no temp copy)
  - const vs constexpr: const = runtime constant; constexpr = compile time only
  - Signed overflow: UNDEFINED behavior | Unsigned overflow: DEFINED (wraps)
  - Mixing signed/unsigned: signed is implicitly converted to unsigned — DANGER
  - float == : NEVER use; always use fabs(a-b) < epsilon
  - {}-init: forbids narrowing (catches data loss at compile time)
  - NaN: not equal to itself (use std::isnan()); Inf: use std::isinf()

CONTROL FLOW — KEY RULES:
  - switch: only int/char/enum; add break; use [[fallthrough]] C++17
  - else: binds to NEAREST unmatched if (dangling else)
  - do-while: always runs body at least once; use for input validation
  - off-by-one: test with n=0 and n=1; careful with < vs <=
  - &&/||: short-circuits — be careful with side effects in conditions
  - ++i in loops: never slower, communicates intent, safer for iterators

FUNCTIONS — KEY RULES:
  - Overloading: cannot differ by return type alone
  - Default args: right-to-left only; declare in header
  - inline: hint only; modern compilers decide with -O2
  - Tail recursion: last op = recursive call; C++ doesn't guarantee TCO
  - [=] lambda capture: copies at creation time (safe); [&]: dangling risk
  - std::function vs raw ptr: std::function holds any callable; raw ptr = C-compat

ARRAYS — KEY RULES:
  - Access: O(1) | Insert/delete at middle: O(N) | Insert at end: O(1) amortized
  - vector resize: doubles capacity; amortized O(1) push_back; invalidates iterators
  - Cache: arrays > linked lists due to spatial locality (sequential memory)
  - Row-major: C++ stores row-by-row; iterate row-by-row for cache efficiency
  - Array decay: when passed to function, array becomes pointer (size info lost)
  - sparse array: use unordered_map instead of allocating full array

